  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.6.1`\r\nOS & Version: Windows\r\nCommit hash : v1.6.1\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\nIf a timeout value is provided to debug_traceTransaction, Geth should abort the trace and respond to the request immediately, so the client can take appropriate actions.\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\nGeth appears to continue the trace to the end, and merely reports that the timeout has been exceeded. For example, if a timeout value of 1 second is provided, the trace may still take several minutes.\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\nDo a PUT against geth with the following body:\r\n```{\"id\":1,\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"method\":\"debug_traceTransaction\",\"params\":[\"0x7e97df329e38dcd4c89d0c215bf24588b2b7c0b58e69618138e96eea349a332d\",{\"disableStorage\":true,\"disableMemory\":false,\"disableStack\":false,\"fullStorage\":false,\"timeout\":\"1s\",\"tracer\":\"{step:function(log){},result:function(){return{};}}\"}]}```\r\nGeth needs to have been started with --rpc --rpcaddr 0.0.0.0 --rpcapi \"debug\"\r\n\r\nWarning: I believe 0x7e97df329e38dcd4c89d0c215bf24588b2b7c0b58e69618138e96eea349a332d is a DDoS transaction. This request may take several minutes to complete.",
